         <abstract>
            <p>The option-adjusted spread (OAS) has developed into a popular and powerful tool for portfolio management. The OAS allows the investor to adjust ex ante yields to a consistent basis for comparison. Valuable as it may be, however, this adjustment has some fundamental flaws.</p>
          </abstract>
